Phase 7 #7 — user picks from queued candidates (coverage gate live since Phase 7 #5; per-user 24h cap live since Phase 7 #6; TDD mandatory per Rule 25)

Phase 7 #6 shipped on 2026-05-16 as `5325b8c`:
- apps/web/src/server/trpc/routers/auth.ts — added 2 module constants (PER_USER_RESET_CAP=5, PER_USER_RESET_WINDOW_MS=24h) and a passwordResetToken.count query with 24h gte where clause + early-return on cap-met. Placed AFTER user lookup so unknown emails skip the cap query (preserves no-enumeration: identical {ok:true} shape across unknown / under-cap / cap-met paths).
- apps/web/src/server/trpc/routers/auth.test.ts — added count: vi.fn() to the mock factory; updated existing happy-path to mock count=0; added 2 new cases: cap-engaged (count=5 → ok, no create, no send, count signature asserted) and one-under-cap (count=4 → still mints + sends); updated unknown-email path to assert count is NOT called.
- Defence-in-depth design: per-email LRU (10/min) catches rapid bursts; per-user 24h cap catches sustained low-rate flooding. Without the cap an attacker passing Turnstile could send 14k+ resets per day to one user.
- RED → GREEN proven inline: cap-engaged test failed first (count not called) → after impl, 15/15 auth.test.ts cases pass.
- Coverage on auth.ts: branches 78.94 → 80.95 (new branch exercised); per-file gate (≥75) passes with widened slack.
- 1 new lesson documented: (🟤) per-user 24h cap design pattern — cap placement after user lookup, count primitive vs findFirst+orderBy, per-user.id keying vs per-email.
- Visual QA Rule 16 not applicable (no UI changes). Note for future smoke tests: with cap live, manually requesting >5 resets for the same email in 24h will now silently no-op.

----------------------------------------------------------------------
Candidates (any order, user picks):
----------------------------------------------------------------------

(c) JWT org-slug encoding                   [middleware foundation — high-risk]
    Scope: Tier 3 (~10 files, middleware + auth.config + session callback + all consumers)
    - apps/web/src/server/auth.config.ts — add `organization_slug` to JWT
    - apps/web/src/server/auth.ts — populate from session.user
    - apps/web/src/middleware.ts — resolve tenant from JWT, validate URL ↔ session match (security.md TENANT MIDDLEWARE SAFETY)
    - Test: middleware unit test for tenant-switch attack rejection
    Risk: every authenticated route depends on this; reserve for careful fresh-context session
    Tier 3 → mandatory split via memory-governance §1: probably 3 sub-sessions (auth.config + auth.ts → middleware → consumers).
    Now the highest-impact open ticket; unblocks (e) Socket.IO.

(d) join/[token] tRPC                       [needs LiveKit ⏳ for full integration]
    Unit tests OK against mocked LiveKit token mint; integration deferred until LIVEKIT_API_KEY filled
    Existing getJoinToken in meetingsRouter has 0 test coverage — could pair with this if scope allows.
    Adding tests for getJoinToken would also let us add a per-file coverage gate on meetings.ts.

(e) Socket.IO auth middleware               [depends on (c)]
    Should land AFTER (c) so the JWT contract is stable.

(f) Root landing page                       [verify scope first]
    Current /page.tsx is 11 lines — check PRODUCT.md for what's expected
    Likely Tier 1.

(i) Periodic cleanup of expired/consumed password_reset_tokens
    A BullMQ scheduled job to DELETE consumed tokens > 30 days old and unconsumed
    expired tokens > 7 days. Keeps the table from growing unboundedly.
    Pairs naturally with #6: the new cap-met silent-skip and the cleanup job
    together close the token-table lifecycle. The count query introduced in #6
    stays fast forever if the cleanup runs daily.

(j) Resolve nodemailer HIGH CVE (GHSA-rcmh-qjqh-p98v)    [security — depends on @auth]
    addressparser DoS via recursive calls affects <=7.0.10; we run 6.9.16 pinned for
    Auth.js v5 peer compat. Three documented paths in lessons.md:
      (a) wait for @auth to widen its nodemailer peer range — cleanest, no code changes
      (b) replace nodemailer with a different transport library — touches email.ts + callsites
      (c) document mitigation (server-stamped addresses only, attacker cannot reach the
          vulnerable parser through the password-reset flow) + add `audit-level=critical`
          to .npmrc per phases.md decision tree step 3
    Path (c) is the realistic short-term option; (a) is the long-term hope; (b) is
    last-resort. Decision deserves its own commit + DECISIONS_LOG.md entry.
    Pre-existing on main — flagged during Phase 7 #5 audit; not Phase 7 #6 regression.

----------------------------------------------------------------------
Rule 25 reminder for ALL of the above:
  → Write failing test FIRST (RED), then implementation (GREEN), then refactor.
  → Test patterns: [[trpc-test-pattern]] (Phase 7 #2) + [[meetings-protected-route-test]] (Phase 7 #3) + [[trpc-test-with-env-mock]] (Phase 7 #4).
  → For forms: reuse the [[shadcn-form-primitive]] pattern from Phase 7 #3 (`_meeting-form.tsx` and `_reset-form.tsx` as reference impls).
  → For shared schemas: `<Entity>CreateClientInputSchema` for client-facing input, `<Entity>CreateInputSchema` for admin/internal projection.
  → For new env vars consumed by routers: add `vi.mock("@/env", ...)` to the test file (extends Phase 7 #4 pattern).
  → When a router becomes fully tested (>95% across all four metrics), add a per-file threshold to apps/web/vitest.config.ts to lock the new coverage in. Use the [[vitest-per-file-glob-thresholds]] pattern from lessons.md.
  → Coverage thresholds rise organically — add tests → measure → bump threshold. Do NOT lower thresholds to make a regression "fix" pass.
  → NEW (Phase 7 #6): for any new throttle/cap design on auth flows, follow [[per-user-24h-cap-pattern]] — place after user lookup (not before), use Prisma `count` (not findFirst+orderBy), preserve no-enumeration response shape on cap-met.

Recommended next: (c) JWT org-slug middleware — now the highest-impact open ticket (unblocks Socket.IO and tenant-switch attack hardening). Reserve for a fresh-context careful session; Tier 3 split likely needed (3 sub-sessions). If a small-and-safe ticket is preferred, pick (j) nodemailer mitigation (path c — single commit + DECISIONS_LOG entry + .npmrc tweak) or (i) cleanup job (pairs naturally with the new cap query). Save (d) join/[token] for when LIVEKIT_API_KEY is filled.

Pending Rule 16 follow-up: smoke-test /app/meetings/new in browser after next `pnpm dev` up (Phase 7 #3 carryover). ALSO smoke-test /forgot-password + /reset-password/[token] — public routes, no credentials needed (Phase 7 #4 carryover). With the new 24h cap live, manual /forgot-password smoke for the same email is limited to 5 requests per 24h — use distinct emails or trust the test assertions.
